Introduction

The Gapminder Foundation was founded by Hans Rosling who is Professor of International Health at the Karolinska Institutet in Stockholm, Sweden. The Best Stats Youve Ever Seen is a famous TedTalk lecture given by Hans Rosling. To help him visualise his talk, the team at Gapminder conputed animation with bubble charts, also knows as motion charts. By increase use of statistics and understading the other factors like economic,social, environmental development, Gapminder foundation enhances overall development. TrendAnalyzer is a data visulization software which was developed by Gapminder and then later acquired by Google Inc. in 2007.

Data Description

The Data consists of 6 columns and 41284 rows. The six columns are 6 variables and 41284 observations. This data consists of variables country,year,income,life,population,region. Country represents all the countries. Year represents data from years 1800 to 2015. The regions included are America,East ASia and Pacific, Europe and Central Asia, Middle East and North Africa,South Asia,Sub-Saharan Africa. It appears that this data has been merged from different datasets.

QUESTION 5 Show the number and/or proportion of countries with low life expectancy over time by region.

##Lets select the base of low lifeExp as 60
lowlifeExpectancy=60

Calculate he proportion of countries with low life expectancy over time by region

## Caluclating the  proportion of countries with low life expectancy over time by region
ProportionlowlifeExp <- ddply(ds, ~ region + Year, function(x) c(
     lowlifeExpectancy = sum(x$life <= lowlifeExpectancy)/nrow(x)) )
##Plottig the data with stripplot, also we are changing the default y-axis to display from 0% to 100%
stripplot(lowlifeExpectancy~Year,ProportionlowlifeExp,group=region,auto.key=TRUE,ylim=c(0,100),ylab="percentage of Low LifeExp country")

QUESTION 6 Find countries with sudden, substantial departures from the temporal trend in income

##Fitting a linear model 
yearMin <- min(ds$Year)
jFunc <- function(x) {
   jiFit <- lm(life ~ I(Year - yearMin), x)
   jiCoef <- coef(jiFit)
   names(jiCoef) <- NULL
   return(c(intercept = jiCoef[1],
            slope = jiCoef[2],
            maxResid = max(abs(resid(jiFit)))/summary(jiFit)$sigma))
  }
lm <- ddply(ds, ~ Country, jFunc)
